== 3...c5 · Botvinnik-Carls defence ==

This is Black's second most common option, after [[../3...Bf5|3...Bf5]]. It is an attack on the base of White's pawn chain.

After [[/4. dxc5|'''4. dxc5''']], Black can eventually recover the pawn with ...e6 and ...Bxc5, though there is usually no hurry and it's not in White's best interests to hold onto the c-pawn too tightly. One line is 4...Nc6 (the e5-pawn is now loose) 5. f4 e6 6. Be3 d4 7. Bf2 Bxc5{{chess/not|+}}. 

[[/4. Nf3|'''4. Nf3''']] allows 4...cxd4 and prepares to recapture the pawn with the knight. 5. Nxd4 Nc6 (e5 is loose) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 prevents Black from developing their light-square bishop actively.

[[/4. c3|'''4. c3''']], preparing to recapture on d4 with a pawn, is a minor sideline but very common in amateur play. Black does not need to take d4 straight away: they can leave the tension and focus on development. 

=== History ===
This line is named after World Champion [[w:Mikhail Botvinnik|Mikhail Botvinnik]] and [[w:Carl Carls|Carl Carls]]. 

Carls had one of the earliest appearances of the line in Breslau, 1912.<ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1284285 Treybal v Carls, 1912. Chessgames.com]</ref> However the line remained uncommon until Botvinnik relied upon it in his [[w:World Chess Championship 1961|1961 rematch]] with [[w:Mikhail Tal|Mikhail Tal]].<ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1032564 Tal v Botvinnik, 1961. Chessgames.com (Round 4)]</ref><ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1032566 Tal v Botvinnik, 1961. Chessgames.com (Round 6)]</ref><ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1032570 Tal v Botvinnik, 1961. Chessgames.com (Round 8)]</ref> Botvinnik won the match and regained the World Championship title.

